    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-02-25T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-02-25T11:00:00-05:00" n="249"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d249">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">835.00/2418c: Circular telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Certain <gloss type="to">Diplomatic Representatives in the American
                            Republics</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="56" xml:id="d249fn56">Sent to Brazil, Peru, Chile, Uruguay, Paraguay,
                        Cuba, Ecuador, Venezuela, Colombia, and Mexico.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-25T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >February 25, 1944—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>For your information and possible use in conversations you may have with
                    officials of the government to which you are accredited the following telegram
                    sent at 1 a.m. today has been received from the American Embassy in Buenos
                    Aires: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I understand that President Ramírez<note n="57" xml:id="d249fn57">Gen.
                                Pedro P. Ramírez. For correspondence on relations between the
                                Ramírez regime and the United States, see <ref target="#pg_228">pp.
                                    228</ref> ff.</note> has presented resignation on grounds of
                            health, apparently under pressure from nationalist extremist elements in
                            Army. Situation at moment is extremely confused, but it would appear
                            that these elements have staged successful counter move against those
                            Ramírez was reported to have under consideration in my 517, February 24,
                            6 p.m.<note n="58" xml:id="d249fn58">Not printed.</note> General
                                Farrell,<note n="59" xml:id="d249fn59">Gen. Edelmiro Farrell,
                                Minister of War under Ramírez.</note> Colonel Perón<note n="60"
                                xml:id="d249fn60">Col. Juan Domingo Perón, Director of the National
                                Department of Labor.</note> and other officers are reported in
                            continuous conference at War Ministry. Colonel Velasco has assumed
                            charge of <pb facs="0306" n="292" xml:id="pg_292"/> capital police
                            headquarters and a Lieutenant Colonel Lagos of Posts and Telegraphs.</p>
                        <p>“A group of approximately 50 army personnel has moved into Union
                            Telefónica Building, apparently to control telephone censorship.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
